Integrating spectral flow and CyTOF data

Christina Bligaard Pedersen

February 19, 2021


This vignette will demonstrate the integration of spectral flow cytometry (SFC) and CyTOF protein expression measurements using cyCombine.


In this vignette, we will perform and dataset integration of the paired CITE-seq/CyTOF dataset from Ferrer-Font et al. (2020).


Ferrer-Font et al. (2020), studied the comparability of CyTOF and SFC data. They used splenocytes from the same samples which had been quantified using the two technologies and were able to conclude that the results were indeed very similar. However, this analysis was carried out by analyzing the sets separately. Here, we would like to demonstrate the direct integration of the sets.

According to the article, the SFC panel of this study contained 21 protein markers, and the CyTOF panel comprised 36 markers. 20 of these were overlapping. A total of five samples are included for each technology, and they are stored at FlowRepository (ID: FR-FCM-Z2GZ) or GitHub. All files were downsampled to 19,858 cells in the analysis of the article and the uploaded FCS files. We downloaded these and relied on one of the GitHub scripts for accurate mapping of channels and markers.

In the original study, they focused on 11 immune cell populations, which were manually gated. Some of these assignments overlap - i.e.T cells were considered as a combined population and after gating on CD4/CD8. The included populations were T cells, CD4 T cells, CD8 T cells, DN T cells, B cells, NK cells, Monocytes, DCs, DC1s, DC2s, and Neutrophils. However, the authors have not shared the cell labels in their FCS files, so we replicated their gating to the best of our ability.

It was already established that the frequencies of these populations correlated nicely between the two technologies, however the article also states that they were unable to overlay the two data types due to the different data structures of the platforms. With this in mind, we enter the path of cyCombine.

We start by loading some packages

library(cyCombine)
library(tidyverse)


Loading data

Spectral flow cytometry data

We are now ready to load the spectral flow data. We have set up a panel file in csv format, so the correct information is extractable from there. Let us have a look at the contents:

# Directory with raw .fcs files
data_dir <- "FR-FCM-Z2GZ/SFC/"

# Panel and reading data
sfc_panel <- read_csv(paste0(data_dir, "/panel_sfc.csv"))
sfc_panel
# A tibble: 30 x 3
   Channel                  Marker      Type 
   <chr>                    <chr>       <chr>
 1 FSC-A                    FSC-A       none 
 2 FSC-H                    FSC-H       none 
 3 FSC-W                    FSC-W       none 
 4 SSC-A                    SSC-A       none 
 5 SSC-H                    SSC-H       none 
 6 SSC-W                    SSC-W       none 
 7 FJComp-AF-A              FJComp-AF-A none 
 8 FJComp-APC-A             KLRG1       type 
 9 FJComp-APC-Fire 750-A    CD45        type 
10 FJComp-Alexa Fluor 532-A FoxP3       type 
#  with 20 more rows


We then progress with reading the spectral flow dataset and converting it to a tibble format, which is easy to process. We use cofactor = 6000 for spectral flow data asinh-transformation as suggested by the original study. Because the FCS files do not contain the marker descriptions we specify these based on the sfc_panel object we prepared.

# Extract the markers to keep
sfc_markers <- sfc_panel %>% 
  dplyr::filter(Type != "none") %>% 
  pull(Marker) %>% 
  str_remove_all("[ _-]")

# Read fcs files and convert to tibble
spectral <- prepare_data(data_dir = data_dir,
                         metadata = paste0(data_dir, "../metadata.xlsx"),
                         sample_ids = 'SampleID',
                         filename_col = "FileName",
                         batch_ids = "Batch",
                         cofactor = 6000,
                         derand = FALSE,
                         markers = sfc_markers,
                         down_sample = FALSE,
                         panel = sfc_panel,
                         panel_channel = 'Channel',
                         panel_antigen = 'Marker')

CyTOF data

We are now ready to load the CyTOF data. Once again, let us have a look at the panel - we also need it here to make our file reading a bit easier.

# Directory with raw .fcs files
data_dir <- "FR-FCM-Z2GZ/CyTOF/"

# Panel and reading data
cytof_panel <- read_csv(paste0(data_dir, "/panel_cytof.csv"))
cytof_panel
# A tibble: 62 x 3
   Channel      Marker         Type 
   <chr>        <chr>          <chr>
 1 Time         Time           none 
 2 Event_length Event_length   none 
 3 Y89Di        89Y            none 
 4 Pd102Di      102Pd          none 
 5 Rh103Di      103Rh          none 
 6 Pd104Di      104Pd_CD45_PBS none 
 7 Pd105Di      105Pd          none 
 8 Pd106Di      106Pd          none 
 9 Pd108Di      108Pd          none 
10 Pd110Di      110Pd_CD45_CpG none 
#  with 52 more rows


And then for the FCS reading and conversion to tibble format. We will employ derandomization and asinh-trasnformation with cofactor = 5.

# Extract the markers to keep
cytof_markers <- cytof_panel %>% 
  dplyr::filter(Type != "none") %>% 
  pull(Marker) %>% 
  str_remove_all("[ _-]")

# Read fcs files and convert to tibble
cytof <- prepare_data(data_dir = data_dir,
                      metadata = paste0(data_dir, "../metadata.xlsx"),
                      sample_ids = 'SampleID',
                      filename_col = "FileName",
                      batch_ids = "Batch",
                      cofactor = 5,
                      derand = TRUE,
                      markers = cytof_markers,
                      down_sample = FALSE,
                      panel = cytof_panel,
                      panel_channel = 'Channel',
                      panel_antigen = 'Marker')

Extracting expression data..
Your flowset is now converted into a dataframe.
Transforming data using asinh with a cofactor of 5..
Done!



Batch correction

Next, we need to figure out which markers to use when integrating the two datasets. From the publication, we know that the overlap is 20 markers - lets verify that to make sure naming matches 1:1.

intersect(sfc_markers, cytof_markers)
 [1] "KLRG1" "CD45"  "FoxP3" "F480"  "CD8a"  "CD11b" "Ki67"  "CD3e"  "Ly6C" 
[10] "CD161" "Ly6G"  "CD11c" "CD45R" "XCR1"  "CD44"  "CD279" "CD274" "CD4"  
[19] "CD69"  "MHCII"


Now, we are ready to combine the two datasets on the overlapping columns.

# Get overlapping column names
overlap_cols <- intersect(colnames(spectral), colnames(cytof))

# Make one tibble
uncorrected <- bind_rows(cytof[,overlap_cols], spectral[,overlap_cols]) %>%
  mutate(id = 1:(nrow(cytof)+nrow(spectral)))

And now, batch correction can be performed with cyCombine. We use rank for normalization and rlen = 100 because these are data from two different technologies.

# Run batch correction 
corrected <- uncorrected %>%
  batch_correct(xdim = 8,
                ydim = 8,
                norm_method = 'rank',
                ties.method = 'average',
                rlen = 100)


Evaluating performance

We now evaluate the correction using EMD - each marker is evaluated across all cells.

corrected$label <- uncorrected$label <- 1 # We set all labels to 1 in order to evaluate globally

emd <- evaluate_emd(uncorrected = uncorrected,
                    corrected = corrected)

cowplot::plot_grid(emd$violin, emd$scatterplot)


Finally, let us look at some plots to visualize the correction. First, the marker distributions before and after:

plot_density(uncorrected, corrected, ncol = 4)

Finally, some UMAPs to visualize the correction. I will downsample to 10,000 cells from each dataset so it is easier to see what is going on.

inds <- split(1:length(uncorrected$batch), uncorrected$batch)
sample <- unlist(lapply(inds, sample, 10000))

plot1 <- plot_dimred(uncorrected[sample,], name = 'Uncorrected', type = 'umap')
plot2 <- plot_dimred(corrected[sample,], name = 'Corrected', type = 'umap')

cowplot::plot_grid(plot1, plot2)
